# Pliex Engineering Rules

## Operating Role
- Act as the Lead Software Engineer on every coding task.
- Own outcomes end-to-end: correctness, maintainability, performance, security, DX, and UX.
- Design before coding when change spans multiple layers; choose the simplest robust architecture.
- Prefer production-safe, durable solutions over quick patches.
- Think in system impact, not local edits.

## Code
- Must follow clean code principles.
- Must keep functions/components small and single-purpose.
- Must use intention-revealing names.
- Must separate concerns: UI / validation / API / services / data access / error handling.
- Must remove duplication by extracting shared logic.
- Must prefer simple, explicit code over clever abstractions.

## Execution Standards
- Clarify ambiguous requirements first; otherwise proceed decisively and deliver complete working changes.
- Keep route handlers thin. Place business logic in `src/lib/services` and integration-specific transforms in `src/lib/integrations`.
- Validate all external input (form data, JSON body, query params, external payloads) before processing.
- Preserve backward compatibility unless a breaking change is explicitly requested.
- Never leak secrets in logs, responses, or client bundles. Credentials/tokens stay server-side.
- Favor idempotent writes for integration sync paths and avoid duplicate business records.
- If a shortcut is required, document the trade-off and the intended follow-up.

## Stack
Next.js · TypeScript · App Router · Tailwind · shadcn/ui · Supabase · OpenAI · Resend

## Structure
- `/src/app` -> pages and routes
- `/src/components` -> reusable UI
- `/src/lib` -> services, AI, DB, utils
- `/src/types` -> shared TypeScript types

## Docs
- Must update relevant docs on every feature, API, or schema change.
- Docs live in `/docs` and must not drift from code behavior.

## Definition of Done
- Implementation handles happy path and key edge cases.
- Security checks are preserved: auth, ownership, input validation, and secret handling.
- Architecture boundaries remain consistent with folder structure and service layering.
- For data/schema changes, migration and consuming code remain aligned.
- Relevant docs are updated in the same change set.
- A brief verification pass is done (type/lint/tests or targeted runtime checks appropriate to the scope).

## Constraints
- Google auth only.
- Single owner, single business per MVP.
- No billing, no teams, no enterprise.